name: PCTGFEContributorTask
title: PCT GFE Contributor Task
description: The PCT GFE Contributor Task is used by a GFE coordinator   to assign a GFE contributor task to a specific provider and may include information specific to that patients expected service

element.definition: A task to be performed.

The narrative need not encode all the structured data, but is required to contain sufficient detail to make it "clinically safe" for a human to just read the narrative. Resource definitions may define what content should be represented in the narrative to ensure clinical safety.
element.comment: Contained resources do not have narrative. Resources that are not contained SHOULD have a narrative. In some cases, a resource may only have text with little or no additional discrete data (as long as all minOccurs=1 elements are satisfied).  This may be necessary for data from legacy systems where information is captured as a "text blob" or where text is additionally entered raw or narrated and encoded information is added later.

element.definition: BasedOn refers to a higher-level authorization that triggered the creation of the task.  It references a "request" resource such as a ServiceRequest, MedicationRequest, ServiceRequest, CarePlan, etc. which is distinct from the "request" resource the task is seeking to fulfill.  This latter resource is referenced by FocusOn.  For example, based on a ServiceRequest (= BasedOn), a task is created to fulfill a procedureRequest ( = FocusOn ) to collect a specimen from a patient.

element.definition: An identifier that links together multiple tasks and other requests that were created in the same context.
element.requirements: Billing and/or reporting can be linked to whether multiple requests were created as a single unit.

element.definition: Task that this particular task is part of.
element.comment: This should usually be 0..1.
element.requirements: Allows tasks to be broken down into sub-steps (and this division can occur independent of the original task).

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The current status of the task.
element.requirements: These states enable coordination of task status with off-the-shelf workflow solutions that support automation of tasks.

element.definition: An explanation as to why this task is held, failed, was refused, etc.
element.comment: This applies to the current status.  Look at the history of the task to see reasons for past statuses.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: Contains business-specific nuances of the business state.
element.requirements: There's often a need to track substates of a task - this is often variable by specific workflow implementation.

element.short: unknown | proposal | plan | order | original-order | reflex-order | filler-order | instance-order | option
element.definition: Indicates the "level" of actionability associated with the Task, i.e. i+R[9]Cs this a proposed task, a planned task, an actionable task, etc.
element.comment:
This element is immutable.  Proposed tasks, planned tasks, etc. must be distinct instances.

In most cases, Tasks will have an intent of "order".

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

binding.description: Distinguishes whether the task is a proposal, plan or full order.

element.definition: Indicates how quickly the Task should be addressed with respect to other requests.
element.requirements: Used to identify the service level expected while performing a task.
element.meaningWhenMissing: If missing, this task should be performed with normal priority

element.definition: A name or code (or both) briefly describing what the task involves.
element.comment: The title (eg "My Tasks", "Outstanding Tasks for Patient X") should go into the code.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

binding.description: Codes to identify what the task involves.  These will typically be specific to a particular workflow.

element.definition: A free-text description of what is to be performed.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The request being actioned or the resource being manipulated by this task.
element.comment: If multiple resources need to be manipulated, use sub-tasks.  (This ensures that status can be tracked independently for each referenced resource.).
element.requirements: Used to identify the thing to be done.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The entity who benefits from the performance of the service specified in the task (e.g., the patient).
element.requirements: Used to track tasks outstanding for a beneficiary.  Do not use to track the task owner or creator (see owner and creator respectively).  This can also affect access control.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: Healthcare event during which this task originated

element.short: Logical reference, when literal reference is not known
element.definition: An identifier for the target resource. This is used when there is no way to reference the other resource directly, either because the entity it represents is not available through a FHIR server, or because there is no way for the author of the resource to convert a known identifier to an actual location. There is no requirement that a Reference.identifier point to something that is actually exposed as a FHIR instance, but it SHALL point to a business concept that would be expected to be exposed as a FHIR instance, and that instance would need to be of a FHIR resource type allowed by the reference.
element.comment:
When an identifier is provided in place of a reference, any system processing the reference will only be able to resolve the identifier to a reference if it understands the business context in which the identifier is used. Sometimes this is global (e.g. a national identifier) but often it is not. For this reason, none of the useful mechanisms described for working with references (e.g. chaining, includes) are possible, nor should servers be expected to be able resolve the reference. Servers may accept an identifier based reference untouched, resolve it, and/or reject it - see CapabilityStatement.rest.resource.referencePolicy. 

When both an identifier and a literal reference are provided, the literal reference is preferred. Applications processing the resource are allowed - but not required - to check that the identifier matches the literal reference

Applications converting a logical reference to a literal reference may choose to leave the logical reference present, or remove it.

Reference is intended to point to a structure that can potentially be expressed as a FHIR resource, though there is no need for it to exist as an actual FHIR resource instance - except in as much as an application wishes to actual find the target of the reference. The content referred to be the identifier must meet the logical constraints implied by any limitations on what resource types are permitted for the reference.  For example, it would not be legitimate to send the identifier for a drug prescription if the type were Reference(Observation|DiagnosticReport).  One of the use-cases for Reference.identifier is the situation where no FHIR representation exists (where the type is Reference (Any).

To make the use of extensions safe and manageable, there is a strict set of governance  applied to the definition and use of extensions. Though any implementer can define an extension, there is a set of requirements that SHALL be met as part of the definition of the extension.
element.comment: There can be no stigma associated with the use of extensions by any application, project, or standard - regardless of the institution or jurisdiction that uses or defines the extensions.  The use of extensions is what allows the FHIR specification to retain a core level of simplicity for everyone.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children
Must have either extensions or value[x], not both

element.short: Mime type of the content, with charset etc.
element.definition: Identifies the type of the data in the attachment and allows a method to be chosen to interpret or render the data. Includes mime type parameters such as charset where appropriate.
element.requirements: Processors of the data need to be able to know how to interpret the data.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

mapping.map: ED.2+ED.3/RP.2+RP.3. Note conversion may be needed if old style values are being used

element.definition: The human language of the content. The value can be any valid value according to BCP 47.
element.requirements: Users need to be able to choose between the languages in a set of attachments.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The actual data of the attachment - a sequence of bytes, base64 encoded.
element.comment: The base64-encoded data SHALL be expressed in the same character set as the base resource XML or JSON.
element.requirements: The data needs to able to be transmitted inline.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: Uri where the data can be found
element.definition: A location where the data can be accessed.
element.comment: If both data and url are provided, the url SHALL point to the same content as the data contains. Urls may be relative references or may reference transient locations such as a wrapping envelope using cid: though this has ramifications for using signatures. Relative URLs are interpreted relative to the service url, like a resource reference, rather than relative to the resource itself. If a URL is provided, it SHALL resolve to actual data.
element.requirements: The data needs to be transmitted by reference.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

mapping.map: RP.1+RP.2 - if they refer to a URL (see v2.6)

element.short: Number of bytes of content (if url provided)
element.definition: The number of bytes of data that make up this attachment (before base64 encoding, if that is done).
element.comment: The number of bytes is redundant if the data is provided as a base64binary, but is useful if the data is provided as a url reference.
element.requirements: Representing the size allows applications to determine whether they should fetch the content automatically in advance, or refuse to fetch it at all.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The calculated hash of the data using SHA-1. Represented using base64.
element.comment: The hash is calculated on the data prior to base64 encoding, if the data is based64 encoded. The hash is not intended to support digital signatures. Where protection against malicious threats a digital signature should be considered, see [Provenance.signature](http://hl7.org/fhir/R4/provenance-definitions.html#Provenance.signature) for mechanism to protect a resource with a digital signature.
element.requirements: Included so that applications can verify that the contents of a location have not changed due to technical failures (e.g., storage rot, transport glitch, incorrect version).

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: Label to display in place of the data
element.definition: A label or set of text to display in place of the data.
element.requirements: Applications need a label to display to a human user in place of the actual data if the data cannot be rendered or perceived by the viewer.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.definition: The date that the attachment was first created.
element.requirements: This is often tracked as an integrity issue for use of the attachment.

constraint.human: All FHIR elements must have a @value or children

element.short: GFE Contributor specific time period the requested GFE should be provided in
element.comment: Indicates the start and/or end of the period of time when the GFE bundle should be provided. Usually this is the same as the GFE Coordination Task, and if so, should not be specified in the provider specific task. However, there may be circumstances in which a specific GFE contributor may have a different timeline that should be included in the provider specific task (e.g. the provider was added to original request afterwards, in the case of a provider replacement; or there is a potential dependency on the provider's response).

element.short: Instant from which the request is being initiated. For patient initiated requests, this is the date and time the patient or their representative made the request. For a newly scheduled service, this represents the time of the scheduling activity (as opposed to the planned time of service). For all other requests, the time of the event that triggered the need for an estimate.
GFE contributor specific planned or scheduled period of service the request is about
GFE Coordination Requester Assigned Identifier for GFE Request
Reference to the GFE Coordination Task

element.comment: Generally this will be a reference to a Practitioner, PractitionerRole, or Organization resource residing on the Coordination Platform. If there is a need to express contact information that is specific to the request, and therefore is not included in the information on the Coordination Platform, the reference should point to a server and resource that does not have additional authentication or or authorization requirements.

element.short: GFE Contributor assigned to complete the task
The reasonCode is inherited from the GFE Coordination Task pointed to by Task.partOf
GFE Contributor specific Information and references to service and supporting information, such as Conditions, Observations, and notes
element.comment: Contained or referenced request information bundle made available to a specific GFE contributor that includes information about the products and or services requested and other supporting information, such as Conditions, Observations, and notes

element.short: Any outputs from the GFE Contributor including the GFE Bundle or notes on why the specific task was unable to be completed
element.comment: Any outputs for the GFE Contributor Task which might include notes on why the GFE Contributor Task was unable to be completed.
